164–Female":"1164–Deceased","about 1195":"about 1195","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","Abt 1206":"about 1206","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1178":"1178","Abt 1210":"about 1210","1210":"1210","after 1235":"after 1235","Aldingham, South Lakeland, Lancashire, England":"Aldingham, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Aldingham, Lancashire, England":"Aldingham, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stainford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English:  see  Stainforth  .","2  English:  see  Stanford  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stainforth","meanings":["English: locative name; one group of family names is from Stainforth in Hatfield (near Doncaster, WR Yorks), and another from Stainforth in Giggleswick (near Settle, WR Yorks). The first of these has probably become confused with   Staniforth   (from a locality in Sheffield)."]},{"name":"Stanford","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places so called, including Stanford (Bedfordshire, Kent), Stanford Dingley and Stanford in the Vale (Berkshire), Stanford le Hope and Stanford Rivers (Essex), Stanford Bishop and Stanford Regis (Herefordshire), Stanford on Avon (Northamptonshire), Stanford on Soar (Nottinghamshire), and Stanford on Teme (Worcestershire); also from Stamford (Lincolnshire, Northumberland), Stamford Bridge (East Yorkshire), and Standford in Headley (Hampshire), all of which appear as <i>Stanford</i> in medieval documents. The placenames all derive from Old English <i>stān</i> ‘stone, rock’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’. This surname has been established in Ireland since the 16th century, where it is also found under the variant <i>Stankard</i>.","History: An early bearer of this surname in North America, Thomas Stanford of England, settled in Charlestown, MA, in the mid 17th century and started a family line that includes Leland Stanford (1824–93), the railroad developer who was governor of CA, a US senator, and the founding benefactor of Stanford University."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":37,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":46,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Stainford was born in 1178, in Aldingham, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Stainford, was 18 and his mother, Mrs. John Stainford, was 15. He married Beatrice de Aldringham about 1206, in Aldingham, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1237, in Aldingham, Lancashire, England, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1178–1237":"1178–1237","1178–1210":"1178–1210","1195–1235":"1195–1235","1160–1220":"1160–1220","1164–Female":"1164–Surnud","about 1195":"umbes 1195","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","Abt 1206":"umbes 1206","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1178":"1178","Abt 1210":"umbes 1210","1210":"1210","after 1235":"pärast 1235","Aldingham, South Lakeland, Lancashire, England":"Aldingham, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Aldingham, Lancashire, England":"Aldingham, Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1178–1237":"1178–1237","1178–1210":"1178–1210","1195–1235":"1195–1235","1160–1220":"1160–1220","1164–Female":"1164–Kuollut","about 1195":"noin 1195","1220":"1220","1164":"1164","1195":"1195","1160":"1160","Abt 1206":"noin 1206","1237":"1237","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1178":"1178","Abt 1210":"noin 1210","1210":"1210","after 1235":"1235 jälkeen","Aldingham, South Lakeland, Lancashire, England":"Aldingham, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Aldingham, Lancashire, England":"Aldingham, Lancashire, England"},"fr":{"1178–1237":"1178–1237","1178–1210":"1178–1210","1195–1235":"1195–1235","1160–1220":"1160–1220","1164–Female":"1